    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDef_11">• Proportional segments have equal ratios.
\n • Ratios show how lengths compare.
\n • Units don’t affect proportionality.</string>

    <string name="SectionOneTheoryProperties_11">• Ratios stay constant when units change.
\n • Parallel lines create proportional segments.
\n • Related segments on both sides are proportional.</string>

    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExamples_11">• Construct a fourth segment with given ratios.
\n • Use parallel lines and an arbitrary angle.
\n • Demonstrates geometric proportionality.</string>

    <string name="SectionOneQuiz_11">!!! Solve the Quiz !!!</string>

    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDef_11">• Similar triangles have equal angles and proportional sides.
\n • Their sides share a constant ratio called the ratio of similitude.
\n • Shapes keep the same form but scale differently.</string>

    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryProperties_11">• Similarity is reflexive, symmetric, and transitive.
\n • A line parallel to a triangle side forms a similar triangle.
\n • Triangles are similar by angles, sides, or proportionality tests.</string>

    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryWorkedExamples_11">• Find segment MN parallel to trapezoid bases: ∣MN∣=(2ab)/(a+b).
\n • Use similarity to prove median ratios.
\n • Applies to triangle and parallelogram relations.</string>

